{{other uses}}

A '''župa''' (or '''zhupa''', '''[[županija]]''') is a historical type of administrative division in [[Central Europe]] and the [[Balkans]], that originated in medieval [[List of Slavic cultures|Slavic culture]], often translated into "county" or "district".{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=225, 227}} It was mentioned for the first time in the 8th century. It was initially used by the [[South Slavs|South]] and [[West Slavs]], denoting various territorial units of which the leader was the '''[[župan]]'''. In modern Croatian and Slovenian, the term ''župa'' also means an ecclesiastical [[parish]].{{sfn|Gluhak|1993|p=713}}

==Etymology==
The word "župa" ([[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]] and [[Serbian language|Serbian]] Жупа; adopted into {{lang-hu|ispán}} and rendered in [[Greek language|Greek]] as ''ζουπανία'' (zoupania, "land ruled by a župan") is derived from [[Slavic languages|Slavic]]. Its medieval Latin equivalent was ''comitatus''. It is mostly translated into "county" or "district".{{sfn|Fine|1991|p=304}} According to Kmietowicz, it seems that the territorial organization had been created in Polish territories before the [[Slav Migrations]].<ref name=Kmietowicz>{{cite book |title=Ancient Slavs |author=Frank A. Kmietowicz |publisher=Worzalla Pub. Co. |year=1976 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=amTxAAAAMAAJ |page=185, footnote}}</ref> Some Slavic nations changed its name into "opole", "okolina" and "vierw", but it has survived in ''župan''.<ref name=Kmietowicz/> Some scholars consider the word's older meaning was "open area in the valley".{{sfn|Gluhak|1993|p=713}} This interpretation is confirmed by the Bulgarian ''župa'' (tomb), Polish ''zupa'' and Ukrainian ''župa'' (salt mine), and [[Old Church Slavonic|Old Slavonic]] ''župište'' (tomb).{{sfn|Gluhak|1993|p=713}} As such, the Proto-Slavic ''*župa'' wouldn't derive from ''*gheu-p-'' (with ''*gheu-'' meaning "bend, distort"),{{sfn|Gluhak|1993|p=713}} yet from Indo-European ''*g(h)eup-/*gheub-'' meaning "cavity, pit",{{sfn|Gluhak|1993|p=713-714}} which derives from [[Nostratic languages|Nostratic]] ''*gopa'' meaning "hollow, empty".{{sfn|Gluhak|1993|p=714}} However, [[Albert Bruckner]] suggested the opposite evolution; ''župa'' as a [[back formation]] from title ''[[župan]]'' (for the etymology see corresponding article),{{sfn|Alemany|2009|p=7}} which is a borrowing from [[Iranian languages]] (*''fsu-pāna'', "shepherd").{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=228}}

==Usage of the division==
The division had a widespread distribution, and did not always had a concrete institutional definition.<ref name="Biliarsky">{{cite book |first=Ivan |last=Biliarsky |date=2011 |title=Word and Power in Mediaeval Bulgaria |url=https://books.google.hr/books?id=O-j66lYzINEC |publisher=Brill |pages=368 |isbn=9789004191457}}</ref> The term ''župa'' signified the territorial and administrative unit of a tribe, and later only an administrative unit without tribal feature.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=227}}{{sfn|Gluhak|1993|p=713}} The South Slavs that settled in Roman lands to a certain degree adopted Roman state organization, but retained their own tribal organization.<ref name=ZU-Zupan>{{cite book|title=The Yugoslav village|author=Zagreb. Universitet. Institut za ekonomiku poljoprivrede i sociologiju sela. SOUR za sociologiju sela|publisher=Dept. of Rural Sociology|year=1972|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZQBPAQAAIAAJ|page=39}}</ref> Slavic tribes were divided into fraternities, each including a certain number of families.<ref name=ZU-Zupan/> The territory inhabited by a tribe was a ''župa'', and its leader was the ''župan''.<ref name=ZU-Zupan/>

The ''zhupa'' (plural ''zhupi'') was an administrative unit in the [[First Bulgarian Empire]], a subdivision of a larger unit called ''comitatus''.  In these countries, the equivalent of "county" is "[[judet]]" (from Latin ''judicium'').{{citation needed|date=July 2012}} The [[Croats]] and the [[Slovaks]] used the terms županija and župa for the counties in the [[Kingdom of Croatia (925–1102)|Kingdom of Croatia]] and [[Administrative divisions of the Kingdom of Hungary|Kingdom of Hungary]]. German language translation of the word for those counties was ''[[Comitatus (Kingdom of Hungary)|komitat]]'' (from Latin ''comitatus'', "countship") during the Middle Ages, but later it was ''gespanschaft'' (picking up the ''span'' root that previously came from ''župan'').{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}

===Croatia===
{{Main|Duchy of Croatia|Counties of Croatia}}

The Croatian word župa signifies both a secular unit (county) and a religious unit (parish), ruled over by a "župan" (count) and "župnik" (parish priest).<ref>{{cite book |title=Medioevo: la chiesa e il palazzo : atti del convegno internazionale di studi, Parma, 20-24 settembre 2005 |author=Arturo Carlo Quintavalle, Università di Parma. Centro di studi medioevali, [[Fondazione Cariparma]] |editor=Arturo Carlo Quintavalle |edition=illustrated |publisher=Electa |year=2007 |page=140}}</ref>

Croatian medieval state was divided into eleven ''ζουπανίας'' (zoupanias; župas), and the [[Ban (title)|ban]] ruled over additional three župas [[Krbava]], [[Lika]], and [[Gacka]]).{{sfn|Živković|2012|p=144}}

Today the term ''županija'' is the name for the Croatian regional government, the [[counties of Croatia]]. Mayors of counties hold the title of ''župan'' (pl. ''župani''), which is usually translated as "county prefect". In the 19th century, the counties of the [[Kingdom of Croatia-Slavonia]] were called ''županija''. The Croats preserved the term ''župa'' until the modern times as the name for local clerical units, parishes of the Catholic Church and of the Protestant churches. The parish priest is called ''župnik''.

===Hungary===
{{Main|Ispán}}

In c. 1074, the župa is mentioned in Hungary as ''-spán'', also as ''határispánságok'' (march, frontier county). The derivative titles were ''ispán'', nominated by the king for not defined time, and gradually replaced by ''főispán'' in the 18-19th century; ''megyésispán'', also nominated by the king but could be expelled anytime; ''alispán'' was the leader of the jurisdiction in the county if the 'megyésispán' was not available; ''várispán'' was more linked to the "vár" (fortress) in Hungary in the times of [[Árpád]].

===Serbia===
{{see also|Serbia in the Middle Ages}}

The Serbs in the Early Middle Ages were organized into ''župe'', a confederation of village communities (roughly the equivalent of a county),<ref>{{harvnb|Fine|1991|p=304}}</ref> headed by a local ''župan'' (a magistrate or governor).<ref name=Evansxxi>{{harvnb|Evans|2007|p=xxi}}</ref> Thus the title of [[Grand Župan]] in [[Grand Principality of Serbia|Raška]] in 11th-12th century meant "supreme župan" of župans who ruled over župas.{{sfn|Gluhak|1990|p=227}}

''[[Dušan's Code]]'' (1349) named the administrative hierarchy as following: "lands, cities, župas and krajištes", the župas and krajištes were one and the same, with the župas on the borders were called krajištes (''frontier'').<ref>Radovanović 2002, p. 5</ref> The župa consisted of villages, and their status, rights and obligations were regulated in the constitution. The ruling nobility possessed hereditary allodial estates, which were worked by dependent ''sebri'', the equivalent of Greek ''[[paroikoi]]''; peasants owing labour services, formally bound by decree.<ref name=Anderson290>[https://books.google.com/?id=sP_2-y9zKfgC&pg=PA290 p. 290]</ref>

Though the territorial unit today is unused, there are a number of traditional župe in [[Kosovo]], around [[Prizren]]: [[Sredačka Župa]], [[Sirinićka Župa]], [[Gora (region)|Gora]], [[Opolje]] and Prizrenski Podgor. The Serbian language maintains the word in toponyms, the best known being that of the [[Aleksandrovac|Župa Aleksandrovačka]].

===Slovakia===
The term ''župa'' was popularized in Slovak professional literature in the 19th century as a [[synonym]] to contemporary Slovak term ''stolica'' (county).<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.komunal.eu/images/pdf/Terminologia_verejnej_spravy_na_Slovensku.pdf |title=Terminológia verejnej správy na Slovensku |website=Komunálne výskumné a poradenské centrum |access-date=1 March 2016}}</ref>  After the collapse of the Austro-Hungarian Monarchy, it was used as the official name of administrative units of Slovakia within [[Czechoslovakia]] in 1919 - 1928 and then again in the [[WWII Slovak Republic|Slovak Republic during WWII]] in 1940-1945.<ref>{{cite book|title=Acta Universitatis Carolinae: Geographica, Volume 38, Issue 1|author=Univerzita Karlova|publisher=Universita Karlova.|year=2005|page=146}}</ref> Nowadays, the term is used semi-officially as a short alternative name for the [[Regions of Slovakia|self-governing regions]] of Slovakia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://domov.sme.sk/c/5045338/slovo-zupa-je-praslovanskeho-povodu-aj-tak-ho-nechceme.html |title=Slovo župa je praslovanského pôvodu, aj tak ho nechceme |website=Sme |date= 3 October 2009 |access-date=1 March 2016}}</ref> President of the self-governing region is semi-officially called ''župan''.

===Slovenia===
During [[World War II]], when [[Slovenia]] was partitioned between Italy, Hungary, and Germany on 17 April 1941, in the Italian portion, named province of [[Ljubljana]], the new administration was led by an Italian High Commissioner, but there also were Presidents of the Council of Zhupans of Ljubljana: [[Marko Natlačen]] (1941), [[Leon Rupnik]] (1942-1943).{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}

